{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum Hamming weight of the product 2023 * n. Since 2023 is not a power of 2, k(n) can be small. This is equivalent to finding the minimum number of ones in a multiple of 2023. This is a classic problem related to the order of 2 modulo the odd part of the number.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Analyze the number 2023. Determine its prime factorization. Note that 2023 = 7 * 17^2. Since 2023 is odd, the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum number of ones in a multiple of 2023. Specifically, investigate if there exists an n such that 2023 * n = 2^a - 1 or 2^a + 2^b + ... for a small number of terms. Check if k(n) = 1 is possible (only if 2023 is a power of 2, which it is not). Check if k(n) = 2 is possible by checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b for some a, b, or equivalently if 2023 divides 2^m + 1 or 2^m - 1 for some m."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Test the possibility of k(n) = 2. This occurs if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b. This is equivalent to 2^(a-b) = -1 mod (2023 / gcd(2023, 2^b)). Since 2023 is odd, this simplifies to checking if -1 is in the cyclic subgroup generated by 2 modulo 2023. Calculate the order of 2 modulo 7 and modulo 289 (17^2). Use the Chinese Remainder Theorem to determine if there exists an integer m such that 2^m = -1 mod 7 and 2^m = -1 mod 289. If such an m exists, k(n) = 2. If not, test if k(n) = 3 is possible by checking if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b + 2^c."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the results from helper 1 and helper 2. Helper 1 establishes the lower bounds and the strategy. Helper 2 provides the rigorous verification of whether k(n) can be 2 by checking the existence of a solution to 2^m = -1 mod 2023 using the orders of 2 modulo the prime factors of 2023. If k(n)=2 is impossible, evaluate the next smallest possible value."
}

